WEST NILE VIRUS UPDATE - CANADA (08)
************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In these updates:
[1] Ontario - 9 confirmed and 19 probable human cases
[2] Manitoba - equine cases total 99
[3] Quebec - first confirmed human case
******
[1]
Date: Fri 27 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ontario Ministry of Health and Long Term Care, Fri 27 Sep 2002 [edited]
<http://www.gov.on.ca/health/english/program/pubhealth/wnv_mn.html>

Ontario: West Nile Virus Update - 9 confirmed and 19 Probable Human Cases
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Ontario Ministry of Health and Long Term Care reported the following
West Nile virus test results.
Birds:
As of Fri 27 Sep 2002, there have been 240 confirmed cases and 1 probable
case of West Nile virus infection of birds, originating from 36 regions of
the province.
Mosquitoes:
As of Fri 27 Sep 2002, 83 pools of mosquitoes have tested positive for West
Nile virus. The pools originated from 13 regions of the province; the
majority from Hamilton, Peel, and Toronto.
Equines:
As of Fri 27 Sep 2002, a total of 5 horses in Hamilton-Wentworth, Lambton,
Niagra, Toronto, and Windsor-Essex have tested positive (i.e. confirmed)
for West Nile virus infection, and a further 31 horses in Windsor-Essex and
one in Toronto are presumed West Nile virus-positive.
Humans:
As of Fri 27 Sep 2002, there have been 9 confirmed and 19 probable cases of
West Nile virus infection in the province: Haldimand-Norfolk 1 probable;
Halton 4 confirmed, 2 probable; Middlesex-London 1 probable; Niagra 2
probable; Peel 4 confirmed, 5 probable; Toronto 6 probable; Windsor 1
confirmed, 1 probable; York 1 probable. One person has died as a
consequence of West Nile virus infection.
As of Mon 25 Sep 2002, the 9 confirmed cases (6 males, 3 females) have a
mean age of 59, a median age of 60, and an age range of 44-74. The 17
probable cases (9 males, 8 females) have a mean age of 54, a median age of
57, and an age range of 21-79.
******
[2]
Date: Fri 27 Sep 2002
From: smacbean <s.macbean@sasktel.net>
Source: Government of Manitoba, news release, Bulletin 28, Thu 26 Sep 2002
[edited]

Manitoba: West Nile Virus Update - 99 Confirmed Equine Cases
--------------------------------------------------
Birds
10 more birds have tested positive for West Nile virus:
Winnipeg (6 crows, 1 blue jay),
Killarney (1 crow),
Morris (1 crow),
RM of St. Clements (1 blue jay).
The total number of confirmed positive birds from the crow family is 88.
Equines
13 more horses have been confirmed positive for West Nile virus:
RM of Springfield(2)
RM of Rosedale
RM of Morton(2)
RM of Lorne(2)
RM of Hanover
RM of Dufferin
RM of Whitehead
RM of Dauphin
RM of Coldwell
RM of Stanley
The total number of confirmed positive horses in Manitoba is now 99 (10
horses were counted twice and have been removed from the data).
Humans:
There have been no human cases of West Nile virus diagnosed in Manitoba.
The risk of illness for any individual remains low and is diminishing as
the weather gets colder. New populations of mosquitoes are less likely to
be infected at this time of year.
The province's summer bird surveillance program will come to an end on Fri
27 Sep 2002. Surveillance of West Nile virus in horses will continue until
mid-October. Surveillance of West Nile virus in humans will continue.
--
smacbean
<s.macbean@sasktel.net>
